Perhaps my favorite place to eat in Brooklyn. Be forewarned, it’s hard to have a light meal here. The portions are hearty, even the salads.  The burgers are to die for. Served inside a Lagos roll (crispy and crunchy on the outside), all the flavors of the meat and the creative toppings like pungent cheeses, pickled vegetables, sauces, are sealed within, and it’s delicious work of art.  I’ve had most things on their menu and there are no weak spots. If you like beats, they incorporate them into many dishes and even their own signature sauces like beat ketchup and a house hot sauce.  Pickled vegetables are also ever-present. They also rotate some dishes seasonally so it’s never stagnant. Their brunch menu is just as good and the burgers are available as well.  The staff is wonderful and attentive. Overall, this place is no frills, not gimmicky, reasonably priced given the quality, and is also enjoyed in repeat visits. I love taking my friends and family here. Five stars well-earned.

Fresh and delicious farm to table food! I started coming here after trying their sister location, Brooklyn Beets Company. Both locations serve the same menu. But Korzo is more spacious and has a lot more seating so I usually come here. They are known for their korzo "fried" burgers, which is what I always get when I visit! Love the concept of a burger wrapped up in a bun. The meat are made of creative ingredients put together, cooked to perfection and juicy. The bun was thin, slightly crunchy and chewy, and holds the burger patty perfectly. This is really one of the best and unique burgers in Brooklyn! Must try!  They also have variant of beet themed items, from beets martini (delish!), homemade beets ketchup and hot sauce (must use for dipping sauce), beet carrot cake, beets burger, roasted beets as sides, and even beets served in some of their entrees.

A rare gem. When you want a burger and your dining companion wants a salad, there are precious few establishments that can produce exceptional plates for both. Korzo does. I ate the platonic form of a burger here, and the “new crop” salad was creative, delicious, healthy and generously-portioned. Coupled with attentive and friendly service, an impressive cocktail, and a surprisingly reasonable bill, this place has rocketed to the top of my go-to list in this neighborhood.

Haven’t been to Korzo in a while, and management was so rude last night when we tried to go. So this is a review about service and not food, as we never got the chance to eat there last night. We called to make a reservation for a party of 7 with 2 high chairs and they said they don’t take reservations on the weekend, but it shouldn’t be a problem early Sunday night. We get there with our out of town friends driving back to PA that night and it is in fact a problem, because they have too many folks seated at the low tables in the back and not enough high tables for a group to accommodate high chairs. That in and of itself isn’t completely their fault, but then they strangely refused to put us on a waiting list and said we had to physically wait in front of the bar with little space and 3 kids under 3. We picked Korzo to eat at because we thought it was a kid friendly neighborhood place. Now won’t come back. Staff was too rude.

I don't remember what was in it but it tasted so darn perfect along with the house made hot sauce and beer ketchup. My girlfriend ordered the Slav which was also delicious but I liked the chef more.  When you come to eat at Korzo, you have to try the beet ketchup and the housemate hot sauce. The hot sauce in my opinion was better and it was so good I tried to buy a bottle. Sad to say they had no more left. I can't wait to come back for another burger and more of that hot sauce.
